Analog video surveillance systems historically appeared first. In general, analog video surveillance systems consist of:

  • Analog video cameras.
  • Digital Video Recorder (DVR – Digital Video Recorder).
  • Auxiliary equipment.

Analog video camera senses video input, produces it processing and sends in analog form to the DVR.

Analogue camcorders allow PAL image transmission or NTSC, which determines the maximum resolution of the transmitted signal: 960x576 pixels at 25 (PAL) and 30 (NTSC) frames per second.

Light flux captured by a camera lens is subject to onto a CCD matrix and converted into an electrical signal transmitted through a cable to a receiving device.

 

 

Drawing x.x – General scheme of operation of an analog video surveillance camera

The camcorder is connected to the DVR using a coaxial cable and connector type BNC.

 

Drawing x.x – BNC connector

DVR (Digital Video Recorder, DVR, Digital Video Recorder) — a device designed to record, store and play video information. A digital video recorder is an electronic device similar in structure to a computer or a video server and contains an ADC, a processor, a hard disk and other components.

 

Drawing x.x – DVR General Diagram

Auxiliary equipment for analog video surveillance systems is various interface converters, video signal extenders, transceivers and other equipment.

Analog CCTV Benefits:

  • Easy to install and configure;
  • Cheapness;
  • Hardware versatility

Disadvantages of analog CCTV:

  • The maximum resolution of an analog video camera is limited.
  • Requiring a direct connection from the camera to the DVR, which can increase the length of the cable lines.
  • Low noise immunity of the signal.

Analog High Definition Surveillance Systems Definition - AHD). This system is a conventional analog system with a similar construction scheme, however, instead of standard video signal transmission formats (PAL and NTSC), proprietary formats are used to transmit the signal in higher resolution.

AHD Benefits:

  • Cheap.
  • Easy to setup and install.
  • Sufficiently high resolution video cameras.
  • Backwards compatible with analog video surveillance systems.

AHD Disadvantages:

  • Proprietary formats and hardware incompatibility.
  • Requiring a direct connection from the camera to the DVR, which can increase the length of the cable lines.
  • Low noise immunity of the signal.

 

Currently, analog video surveillance systems are practically not used, due to the requirement of the law, which describes the need to use only IP video surveillance systems at facilities.
